  "prompt": "Do the prime minister of our country require visa to visit any country?",
  "response": "Whether a Prime Minister requires a visa to visit another country depends on several factors, including their nationality, the country they are visiting, and the purpose and duration of the visit.\n\nHere's a general breakdown:\n\n*   **Diplomatic Passport:** Prime Ministers (and other high-ranking government officials) typically travel on diplomatic passports. These passports often grant visa-free access or expedited visa processing to many countries.\n*   **Bilateral Agreements:** Many countries have agreements waiving visa requirements for diplomatic passport holders of specific nationalities.\n*   **Purpose of Visit:** The purpose of the visit matters. An official state visit is usually pre-arranged, and the host country will ensure the necessary clearances and permissions are in place, often waiving visa requirements.\n*   **Reciprocity:** Visa policies are often based on reciprocity. If one country grants visa-free access to diplomatic passport holders from another country, the other country will likely do the same.\n\nTo get a definitive answer for a specific Prime Minister and country, you would need to consider:\n\n1.  The Prime Minister's nationality\n2.  The specific country they wish to visit\n3.  Any existing visa agreements between the two countries regarding diplomatic passport holders.\n\nYou can often find this information on the foreign ministry websites of both countries.\n",
